Enum ProtocolOperationResult

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<ProtocolOperationResult>
      • me.pagekite.glen3b.library.bukkit.protocol.ProtocolOperationResult
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<ProtocolOperationResult>

    public enum ProtocolOperationResult
extends java.lang.Enum<ProtocolOperationResult>
    Represents the result of an operation involving or relating to protocol modification. This enum represents specific cases that are documented in further detail with each method that returns this type.
    Author:
    Glen Husman

    • Enum Constant Summary

      Enum Constants 
      Enum Constant and Description
      FAILURE
      Represents a generic protocol operation failure.
      FAILURE_INCORRECT_ARGUMENT_TYPE
      Represents a protocol operation failure due to an argument not being of the correct reflective type.
      LIBRARY_NOT_AVAILABLE
      The protocol operation failed because an appropriate library was not available to handle the necessary operations required for the operation's completion.
      NOT_NEEDED
      Represents that a protocol operation cannot happen without conflicting with existing data.
      SUCCESS
      Represents a successful operation that has taken place and the intended result was the actual result.
      SUCCESS_QUEUED
      Represents a successful operation that has not yet taken place, but should unless an unexpected error occurs.

      • FAILURE_INCORRECT_ARGUMENT_TYPE

        public static final ProtocolOperationResult FAILURE_INCORRECT_ARGUMENT_TYPE
        Represents a protocol operation failure due to an argument not being of the correct reflective type. This value may be returned when a CraftBukkit implementation class is expected, but a Bukkit API type is given. This value should only be returned if an argument is of the incorrect runtime type. The closest possible type should be enforced at compile time.

      • SUCCESS_QUEUED

        public static final ProtocolOperationResult SUCCESS_QUEUED
        Represents a successful operation that has not yet taken place, but should unless an unexpected error occurs.

      • SUCCESS

        public static final ProtocolOperationResult SUCCESS
        Represents a successful operation that has taken place and the intended result was the actual result.

      • NOT_NEEDED

        public static final ProtocolOperationResult NOT_NEEDED
        Represents that a protocol operation cannot happen without conflicting with existing data. This value will only be returned if the intended result is already present without packet modification. Calling succeeded() on this value will return true.
